@kxepal handled the `license.skip` & `src/Makefile.am` bits. `worker-javascript.js` didn't have a license header either (they're both from https://github.com/ajaxorg/ace-builds/ fwiw). Those can be added, of course. Just let me know if they're needed (I think they are, but would like a confirmation).

Also, good thoughts on the other language stuff.

@garrensmith and I are talking about how to make this an extension rather than a direct change to `documents/views.js`. That should provide for some more interesting modularity.

@benoitc It would be much more helpful if you commented on lines using the "Files Changed" tab. This gives your comments context which is important.

For instance, "why not passing a callback to a multipart decode function?" is not immediately clear. Given that I just read this I think you're referring to `couch_httpd_db:receive_request_data/1` which now uses `couch_httpd:recv_chunked/1`. If so, then he is passing a callback. The issue is that the code that writes this stuff to disk also wants a callback. Basically we have some really crappy interfaces in CouchDB so you occasionally have to do process spawning to connect them together.

I'd also assume that "also, did you removed support for the content-length?" refers to recv_chunked, which I also had to look into. Turns out it proxies to `mochiweb_request:stream_body/4` which handles content-length just fine. The `recv_chunked` was just a terrible naming convention for it.

@deathbearbrown there's now a matching branch on the otherside, so these should be merge-able.

Shoot me screen shoots if you see anything amiss.

@garrensmith wouldn't mind you taking a look also.

@rnewson good call on the date and my too-quick copy paste from MDN's copyright page. They have liberal licenses on their code regardless...but we would need to attribute them in the NOTICE and LICENSE files. etc.

@garrensmith @ziggythehamster @kxepal I'd vote for $.indexOf from jQuery (if it's sufficient) over es5-shim to keep the changes small and targeted and not include more libraries.

@ziggythehamster thanks for being here. Thanks for contributing code. Now it's back to Fauxton for me. :grin:
